{"id":"1312.4431","submitter":"Cosmo Lupo","authors":"Cosmo Lupo, Seth Lloyd","title":"Maximally strong entropic uncertainty relations and gauge invariance","comments":"Paper withdrawn by the authors. We became aware of a flaw in the\n  proof that invalidates the result","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Uncertainty relations are among the unique fingerprints of quantum physics,\nbeing direct expression of non-commutativity and complementarity. Entropic\nuncertainty relations arise in quantum information theory as the most natural\nexpression of the uncertainty principle and have proven themselves important\ntools for cryptographic security proofs. An open question has been how strong\nentropic uncertainty relations can be. Here we answer this question by showing\nthat there exist observables that obey maximally strong entropic uncertainty\nrelations in high dimensional Hilbert spaces. Actually, we show that maximally\nstrong uncertainty relations are typically verified if the observables are\ndistributed somehow uniformly. In particular, we show that phase randomness in\na mutually unbiased basis is sufficient, providing a link between uncertainty\nrelations and local gauge invariance. For quantum systems of finite dimensions\nour approach provides an explicit relation between the strength of the\nuncertainty and its probability.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 16 Dec 2013 17:11:17 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 29 Jan 2014 01:05:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-01-30"}
