:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-03-22"}
{"id":"1312.4790","submitter":"Thomas Brantseg","authors":"Thomas Brantseg, Randall L. McEntaffer, Luke M. Bozzetto, Miroslav\n  Filipovic and Nolan Grieves","title":"A multi-wavelength look at the young plerionic supernova remnant\n  0540-69.3","comments":"35 pages, 17 figures, accepted by ApJ","journal-ref":"ApJ 780, 50-72, 2014","doi":"10.1088/0004-637X/780/1/50","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a study of the plerionic supernova remnant 0540-69.3 in the LMC in\nX-ray, radio, optical, and infrared. We find that the shell of 0540-69.3 is\ncharacterized in the X-ray by thermal nonequilibrium plasma with depleted Mg\nand Si abundances and a temperature of kT ~ 0.7 keV. This thermal emission is\nsuperimposed with synchrotron emission in several regions. Based on X-ray\nspectra and on morphological considerations in all surveyed wavebands, we\nconclude that the shell is expanding into a clumpy and highly inhomogeneous\nmedium. In one region of the shell we find an overabundance of Ne, suggesting\nthe presence of ejecta near the edge of the remnant. We also see evidence for\nreheating of material via a reverse shock originating from the interaction of\nthe supernova blast wave with a particularly dense cloud in the surrounding\nmedium. Finally, we perform the first detailed study of the \"halo\" region\nextending 1.2-2.2 pc from the central pulsar. We detect the presence of thermal\nand nonthermal spectral components but do not find evidence for mixing or\nejecta. We conclude that the thermal component is not a counterpart to similar\noptical and infrared halos and that it is most likely due to the projection of\nshell material along the line of sight.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 Dec 2013 14:01:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-12-18"}
